<TEXT>
in the year since he lost his legs trying 
to block a trainload of munitions s brian willson has become a 
symbol of inspiration in the movement for peace in central america 
hundreds have been stirred to maintain roundtheclock protests 
at the concord naval weapons station since last sept 1 the day 
the slowmoving navy train under orders not to stop rolled over 
willson as he sat on the tracks the demonstrators surrounded by 
picket signs sleeping bags and american flags stand by as trains 
and trucks carry weapons across port chicago highway which cuts 
through the base 
because of what i chose to do and what the navy chose to do 
im a symbol and that can be used for good i think willson 47 
said this week in an interview at the san franciscobased institute 
for the practice of nonviolence which he founded with his wife 
holly rauen 
the softspoken willson a vietnam veteran born on the fourth of 
july and raised in a conservative politically inactive family in 
ashville ny said hes more convinced than ever of the need to 
campaign for peace and a halt to weapons shipments to central 
american nations 
i dont think it was a mistake and i dont regret what i did 
im sorry the train ran over me and that i lost my legs its a 
drag he said i feel more liberated than ever to speak the 
truth so i dont have any desire or wish to back off he said 
in the past year willson has spoken across the country at the 
scene of the accident 40 miles east of san francisco 
demonstrations prayers rallies and civil disobedience still 
elicit headlines thanks to highprofile protesters such as the 
rev jesse jackson joan baez martin sheen author alice walker 
and peace activist daniel ellsberg 
an ecumenical service will be held at the weapons station 
thursday to mark the anniversary of willsons maiming 
it will be the first time since june 10 that willson has visited 
the spot where he inspires protesters but riles many of the 450 
people in the adjacent town of clyde who have grown weary of the 
sight and sound of demonstrators on their doorstep 
when demonstrators posted a handmade sign reading brian 
made to look like the town sign of clyde across the road from 
the base gates residents were outraged the sign came down after a 
session with a county mediator 
don elam is typical of most townspeople today he complains the 
protest site is an eyesore and demonstrators are leftwing 
radicals who sympathize with communist governments 
the protesters meet with a wide range of responses earlier this 
week 19yearold spaulding brook of vermont was leaning on the 
base fence near a sign reading wage peace when a man drove 
past blared boo through a megaphone and gestured obscenely a 
carload of men yelled go home others driving by flash peace 
signs 
the county has spent about 335000 for patrols of contra costa 
sheriffs deputies who have arrested some 325 people since last 
sept 1 according to sgt doug sizemore 
tired of the marathon protest and concerned about safe 
transportation of explosives across a 200foot intersection the 
navy wants to build a 10 million overpass to takes vehicles over 
the highway said base spokesman dan tikalsky 
while the navy seeks funding from the defense department others 
have turned to the courts 
county prosecutors have failed to convict any protesters 
willson has sued the navy and the crew of the train that refused to 
stop and the crew has countersued 
the northern california chapter of the american civil liberties 
union sued to stop use of a painful choke hold on protesters being 
arrested a federal court rejected a county request for permission 
to remove protesters tables chairs and picket signs from the edge 
of the highway 
so the demonstrators remain suffering occasional attacks with 
eggs bottles and obscenities 
chuck goodmacher of the mount diablo peace center in nearby 
walnut creek which helps coordinate the protests says the local 
antagonism is ironic because in 1986 voters only narrowly 
rejected a measure urging the government to halt arms shipments 
through the county until there was a regional peace settlement in 
central america 
sandy hillard is one of the few locals who have joined the 
protests her car has been painted with swastikas pelted with eggs 
and had its tires flattened 
i wish they protest opponents could get to know us better 
before making a judgment hillard said its unfortunate to 
live in a community with fears of getting your house burned down 
</TEXT>
