<TEXT>
sixtyfive years after a killer earthquake and 
ensuing firestorms ravaged a crowded tokyo officials are alerting 
people of the possibility of another massive one 
they say it could come anytime between now and the next 20 years 
and is expected to pack enough power to split the ground 
the authorities are using the sept 1 anniversary of the 1923 
great kanto earthquake to organize information fairs and earthquake 
drills and keep up vigilance among residents accustomed to 
frequent mostly harmless earthly shudders 
were constantly doing pr public relations said takeshi 
yanagida of the tokyo city governments disaster countermeasure 
bureau most people know enough to turn off the gas and keep 
emergency supplies of food water money underwear 
in the event of a second great kanto earthquake what 
authorities can do is limited we need help from the people 
much of japan lies along a major fault at the juncture of 
mammoth tectonic plates shifting slowly across the earths surface 
small earthquakes shake the country every day most of them 
unnoticed by humans but to scientists maintaining a 24hour watch 
they are signs of building pressure that must eventually culminate 
in a powerful release 
the resulting quake they say will likely register an 8 on the 
openended richter scale the mexico city quake of 1985 measured 
81 and will strike under or near the kanto plain surrounding the 
capital or along the crowded 170mile tokai belt linking tokyo and 
the western city of nagoya 
in the worstcase scenario the quake will come on a winter 
evening when people are cooking their dinners a day with a dry 
northeasterly wind of about 22 kilometers per hour 14 mph 
yanagida said 
powerful enough to buckle walls and knock people off their feet 
it could set off fires from gas ranges and heaters that would burn 
half a million homes destroy onethird of tokyos living and 
office space kill 37000 people and injure 78000 more scientists 
say a quake along the tokai belt could kill up to 100000 
the tolls while disastrous would still be only a fraction of 
the human cost of the 1923 disaster 
two minutes before noon on sept 1 1923 the earth rose in a 
violent upheaval experts say that if the richter scale had been 
developed at the time it would have registered 78 the earthquake 
toppled houses and scattered embers from cooking fires sparking 
deadly firestorms that swept the capital regions rickety densely 
packed neighborhoods when the embers had cooled as many as 
140000 people had perished mostly in the fires and billions of 
dollars worth of property lay in ruins or badly damaged 
masatoshi rachi then a 13yearold farmers son in eastern 
tokyo recalled watching the firestorms approach after his familys 
house had withstood the tremor 
all around sparks were falling like rain people were 
climbing onto their roofs and wetting them down he said 
those who had lost their homes were setting up barracks 
finding space with relatives our house which fortunately didnt 
burn was so full there was only room enough for people to sit 70 
or 80 in all relatives and strangers 
rachi is now 78 tougher building standards fire and changes of 
business have forced him to rebuild his home five times each time 
though he has taken care to reinforce beams and to prepare a 
parcel with stores of water food a flashlight medicine 
rachi was not alone in learning lessons from the 1923 disaster 
the government restricted use of building bricks stiffened 
regulations on securing window glass and encouraged pioneering 
architecture and engineering that allow skyscrapers to roll and 
sway instead of buckling during tremors 
it sent teams to study the devastation after the 1971 los 
angeles quake when highways collapsed and the one that shook 
mexicos capital three years ago bringing on massive confusion 
among families searching for their missing 
tokyo now has sturdier supports for its elevated highways and is 
experimenting with a wireless system for emergency communications 
recent experience has taught the japanese they are likely to be 
safer indoors during a quake 
but despite the funds the government has poured into earthquake 
prediction the truth is were not 100 percent sure we can 
predict the big one said hirofumi yokoyama of the meteorological 
agencys earthquake prediction division we can be maybe 80 
percent certain 
the system is such that we should be able to predict a large 
kanto quake two or three days in advance he said we cant 
tell exactly when but we can say about where 
with luck the information will be enough to prevent a 
fullscale repetition of the catastrophe 65 years ago under an 
advanced disastercontrol program trains will stop when a 
tremendous quake occurs public address systems will be triggered 
automatically people will congregate with their emergency kits at 
governmentdesignated sites and roadways will be cleared for 
emergency vehicles 
but the unknown element looms 
im terrified of quakes said the tokyo governments 
yanagida theyre not like typhoons which you can at least see 
earthquakes can intensify after they start 
the thing is you just never know 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

