<TEXT>
first it was the volkswagen beetle then the hardy 
citroen deux chevaux 
now the famed solex motorbike dear to millions in 40 countries 
and for many a symbol of youthful independence is puttering into 
the junkyard of transportation history 
the last solex a fattired bicycle with a tiny motor perched 
atop its front wheel will roll off the assembly line in northern 
city of st quentin at the end of the year victim of poor 
economics and japanese enterprise 
the solex was invented in 1942 and more than 6 million have 
been sold since they run practically forever on just a suspicion 
of gasoline but need a good pedaling to get them rolling up 
anything but the most modest incline 
michele cotta news director for frances tf1 television 
network perhaps summed it up best tears of nostalgia come to my 
eyes not only because like many of us this mode of locomotion 
evokes happy times but with the solex junked its a bit of our 
youth they are destroying 
ungainly poorly balanced and far from elegant the solex 
nonetheless became popular in the 1960s with a top speed of 23 
mph it was a symbol of youth and economy 
motobecane the company that produced bicycles and solexes went 
bust in 1983 resurfacing as mbk industrie with several investers 
including japans yamaha in 1986 yamaha increased its stake in 
the company to 80 percent 
takashi ueoka marketing director for mbk said in an interview 
wednesday the company regretted killing solex but it had to be 
done 
its like the volkswagen beetle said ueoka its the same 
story many people have expressed their regret but we had to make 
a decision of course when i explain the situation they understand 
the solex product is 45 years old he said it has been 
very useful and well used it sold in 40 countries particularly 
africa and nearly all of europe the best year was 1964 when 
380000 were sold in france 
only 2700 found buyers last year even at the price of about 
470 
to better utilize the st quentin plant which also makes 
motobecane bicycles and mopeds the company is investing 28 
million to modernize the equipment and introduce yamaha models to 
the production 
ueoka says economics win out over sentiment every time 
it was my first motor as a teenager when i was 14 said 
parisian christophe cachera i had the impression of speed it 
was also a passage from childhood to adolescence too bad its 
going to disappear if everybody in paris had one life would be a 
lot easier 
alas its only another sign of the times ms cotta wrote in 
the popular daily le parisien 
for how many did the solex mark the first independence the 
first open spaces the first conquests but its condemned to 
death this first bike because the youth of today go faster are 
more in a hurry to achieve maturity 
</TEXT>
