<TEXT>
a federal judges order to protect a 
littleknown species of woodpecker is at the heart of a tugofwar 
between environmentalists and loggers over clearcutting in the 
national forests of texas 
naturalists estimate there are only about 180 to 190 
redcockaded woodpecker colonies left in texas with about two 
birds to a colony compared to the 500 or so needed to maintain a 
viable population 
at issue is us district judge robert m parkers ruling that 
seeks to protect the endangered bird by barring us forest service 
contractors from cutting down entire stands of trees within 
threefourths of a mile of a woodpecker colony restricting the 
harvest of trees near nests and limiting the use of roads near 
where the woodpeckers live or forage 
politicians have been quick to denounce the decision saying the 
restrictions could eliminate hundreds of jobs for truckers 
sawmillers and lumberjacks 
rep jim chapman dtexas says he doesnt care if the 
woodpecker becomes extinct humankind and the biological order 
can get along just fine without this bird he says 
environmentalists say the selective harvesting they advocate 
would require more not fewer loggers than clearcutting which 
is heavily mechanized 
but chapman says he is concerned that the forest service will 
overreact and fail to harvest as much as it still can in the 
sabine davy crockett angelina and sam houston national forests 
forest service spokesman carl gidlund said the judges ruling 
covers 473 miles of roads almost a fourth of the 2000 total 
miles of roads in the four east texas forests 
im encouraging them to cut in as close as they can because 
were talking about jobs says chapman by taking the 
conservative approach theyre not selling the timber under the 
court order i suspect they could sell 
environmentalists contend that clearcutting caused a 
precipitous 10 percent drop in the birds population over the past 
five years and said such timbering practices were violating the 
endangered species act 
parker in his june 17 ruling agreed and told the forest service 
to alter its harvesting practices to unevenage or selection 
management 
parker ordered the agency to file a plan to comply with his 
order but the forest service has responded by proposing a 
compromise between clearcutting and selection management that 
environmentalists oppose a sept 28 hearing is scheduled 
ned fritz of the texas committee for natural resources accuses 
the forest service of intransigence they are sullenly refusing 
to abide by the order of the court he said 
in selection management only certain trees are removed at a 
time so a perpetual forest is maintained fritz said creating the 
best habitat for the bird while also reducing the chances of insect 
infestations additional jobs would be created because more 
foresters are needed to keep track of what trees can be harvested 
he said 
that argument fails to sway chapman 
the real argument is not over the woodpecker but is basically 
environmentalists disagreeing with clearcutting were talking 
about 500 woodpeckers theyre ugly they dont have a particularly 
melodious song and they perform no useful service to either nature 
or man he said 
adds a spokesman for sen phil gramm rtexas clearly one 
side is winning and it seems to be the woodpecker 
gramm chapman and other opponents of the judges order also say 
it will cost local counties money a dozen counties in texas 
receive a fourth of the gross sales from timber harvested in 
federal forests with a total of 37 million last year going into 
local school districts and county road and bridge funds according 
to gramms office 
but fritz an attorney with the environmental group said claims 
that revenues will drop are smoke screens 
the misrepresentations have gone wild he said selection 
management is more costeffective and produces just as much if not 
more timber and leaves the forest everbetter 
