<TEXT>
new measurements have confirmed rapid growth 
in the atmosphere of manmade bromine compounds from fire 
extinguishers that scientists believe help destroy the earths 
protective ozone layer 
bromine has received much less attention than the 
chlorofluorocarbon or cfc compounds in discussions of how to save 
the stratospheric chemical layer that blocks the suns 
cancercausing ultraviolet rays 
but bromine was covered by last years treaty calling for a 
halving of cfc production by 1998 production of the firefighting 
bromine compounds called halons is to be frozen at 1986 levels in 
1992 
a chemical cousin of chlorine bromine by itself can destroy 
little ozone but many chemists believe it amplifies the 
ozonedestroying ability of chlorine liberated from both halons and 
the cfc compounds used as refrigeration fluids solvents foam 
blowing agents and outside the united states as aerosol 
propellants 
other compounds some arising naturally from the ocean are 
important sources of atmospheric bromine there is no consensus on 
the importance of each source and industry appears divided on the 
importance of the new findings 
the firefighting compounds are valuable because they snuff out 
flames while leaving no residue that would disable valuable 
equipment like computers only about 5 percent of emissions is 
believed to come from actual firefighting with most emissions 
coming from equipment testing 
professional groups already have revised codes to eliminate 
requirements that halons be used to test equipment 
the latest halon measurements were made by a team of west german 
and indian scientists based at germanys max planck institute 
in the aug 18 issue of nature the british scientific weekly 
the team reported atmospheric concentrations of the two main halons 
seem to be growing at 12 percent per year and 5 percent per year 
the fastergrowing compound is halon 12 used in portable 
extinguishers whose concentration was measured in balloon flights 
over france and india at 19 parts per trillion at 33000 and 
37000 feet the slower growth is for halon 13 used in 
roomflooding installations whose concentration was about 13 
parts per trillion 
the major cfcs are present at a few hundred parts per trillion 
but the two bromine compounds are far more powerful three and 11 
times as destructive of ozone than the most important cfc compound 
the halon 12 concentrations when compared with measurements 
made in 1982 1983 and 1984 yield growth rates of 12 percent to 20 
percent per year the researchers said 12 percent seems to be the 
more realistic there have been no previous growth rates reported 
for halon 13 
the measurements are in the range we have been considering in 
our models said ross salawitch a postdoctoral researcher in the 
harvard university group headed by michael mcelroy studying bromine 
reactions in the atmosphere 
the mcelroy group believes bromine is responsible for about 20 
percent of the annual loss of ozone over antarctica that produces 
the wellknown september hole which last year saw ozone 
concentrations fall to 50 percent of normal 
some studies also show a small ozone loss over the arctic 
if there is any chemically driven ozone loss over the arctic 
it is more likely to be driven by the chlorinebromine reactions 
salawitch said 
three companies make halon compounds in the united states du 
pont co ici americas and great lakes chemical corp 
at great lakes in west lafayette ind dave bouchard a 
chemical engineer who is director of investor relations said the 
company was not confident at all that bromine enhances the 
ability of chlorine to destroy ozone and was sponsoring and 
conducting research to try to prove or disprove it 
at du pont spokeswoman cathy forte said the nature article was 
generally consistent with our understanding of the effects of 
bromine in the atmosphere and would not affect the companys 
plans to end production of all its ozonedepleting products before 
the turn of the century including halon compounds 
the company has ended equipment testing with halons she said 
dan dudek an atmospheric scientist with the environmental 
defense fund said he believed halon production should be reduced 
just like cfc production 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

