the mexican newspaper editors association on 
wednesday criticized a new law in tamaulipas state that calls for 
jury trials in cases involving crimes committed by the media 
against the public order and security of the state 
the federal code already lists these crimes but the new state 
law subjects defendants to jury trial when committed by the 
press 
the association voiced its opposition to the law on the last day 
an annual convention being held in mexico city with the national 
association of hispanic publications of the united states 
the mexican association boasts 72 newspaper affiliates 
the law calls for potential jurors to be selected by municipal 
mayors to hear accusations against the media 
association president jose martinez bastida said the law 
violates constitutional guarantees and constitutes an attempt 
against freedom of expression and the right to information 
luis villareal marroquin director of the newspaper diario in 
nuevo laredo received the associations jose vansconcelos award 
for his efforts to stop enactment of the state law 
