<TEXT>
the boston symphony orchestra didnt violate 
vanessa redgraves civil rights when it canceled her performances 
after receiving threats of protest over the actress proplo views 
a us appeals court ruled 
the decision by the full 1st us circuit court of appeals 
reversed an earlier finding by a threemember panel of the court 
that the orchestra had violated the massachusetts civil rights act 
the 32 ruling wednesday upheld the first amendment right of the 
orchestra to cancel the performances because of concern over their 
artistic integrity 
we have no reason to think that the massachusetts legislature 
enacted the mcra in an attempt to have its courts at the 
insistence of private plaintiffs oversee the editorial judgments 
of newspapers the speechrelated activities of private 
universities or the aesthetic judgments of artists said judge 
frank m coffin writing for the majority 
however the court reinstated an award of 12000 that ms 
redgrave would have earned in a broadway role she lost during the 
suit against the symphony 
symphony officials were relieved by the ruling said bso 
attorney bob sullivan they can go back to doing what theyre 
best at making music he said 
attorneys for ms redgrave daniel j kornstein and marvin 
wexler did not immediately return calls 
ms redgrave was hired by the symphony in 1982 to narrate six 
performances of stravinskys oedipus rex at boston at 
tanglewood in western massachusetts and at new yorks carnegie hall 
the symphony canceled the contract after it received letters and 
phone calls indicating there would be picketing and other protests 
because of ms redgraves support of the palestine liberation 
organization 
the symphony argued that massachusetts law allowed it to cancel 
performances because of concern that disruptions would mar their 
artistic integrity 
in 1984 a federal jury ruled the symphony breached its contract 
with ms redgrave and awarded her the 27500 she was to have 
received plus 100000 for work ms redgrave said she lost because 
of the cancellation 
a federal judge out the 100000 award in 1985 and ruled the 
symphony had not violated ms redgraves civil rights in october 
the threemember appeals panel restored 12000 of that award but 
agreed that her rights had not been violated 
