<TEXT>
united states and soviet union should halt 
production of a key component of nuclear weapons as a way of pacing 
cuts in their arsenals according to a group of arms control 
specialists 
in an article to be published friday in the journal science the 
group called for stopping further production of tritium a hydrogen 
isotope that decays at a rate of 55 percent yearly tritium is a 
component of the modern compact nuclear warheads deployed by the 
superpowers 
a nuclear weapons scientist from lawrence livermore national 
laboratory however responded that the proposal poses numerous 
problems and could complicate ussoviet arms talks 
advocating the tritium factor as a means of arms control 
were four specialists headed by j carson mark associated with 
the nuclear control institute a washingtonbased policy group 
mark is former leader of the theoretical division at los alamos 
national laboratory 
mark contended that the 55 percent annual decay of tritium 
could serve as a forcing function to produce steady verifiable 
reductions in the superpowers nuclear arsenals such reductions 
would result in a comprehensive 50 percent cut in warheads by about 
12 years after an agreement the year 2001 if the cutoff were to 
begin now 
mutual suspension of new tritium production he wrote would 
represent a shared commitment to keep reductions in nuclear 
armaments going at a steady pace 
mark noted that such a halt also would allay safety concerns 
on both sides associated with continuing to operate their aging 
production reactors 
the preactor at the department of energys savannah river plant 
near aiken sc which produces both tritium and plutonium was 
shut down last month after undergoing a sudden power surge while 
workers were attempting to restart the reactor the plants two 
other production reactors currently are also shut down one for 
maintenance and the other due to safety concerns 
with a halt in tritium production mark said expensive plans to 
upgrade and eventually replace these reactors could be set aside 
the production reactors of both sides would be placed on standby 
ready to restart tritium production only if nuclear arms talks 
break down he wrote 
mark said an agreement to halt nuclear materials production 
could be verified by reconnaissance satellites monitoring 
heatgenerated infrared radiation at the facilities 
any undeclared source of thermal radiation could be challenged 
as a potential clandestine facility and made subject to onsite 
inspection he argued 
in a rebuttal published alongside marks proposal wg 
sutcliffe a scientist with the evaluation and planning program at 
lawrence livermore said that any proposal to limit nuclear 
materials as a means of arms control is premature 
he contended that asymmetries in nuclear materials production 
capabilities design practices and delivery system capabilities 
could lead to disparate impacts on the us and soviet stockpiles 
possibly leaving the us in a vulnerable position 
proposing nuclear materials limits is fraught with great 
uncertainties about the comparability of effects on the two 
stockpiles and verification issues because of the unknowns about 
the soviet stockpile and production capabilities sutcliffe said 
noting that early nuclear weapons did not use tritium he said 
that as a result of the inevitable research efforts new 
technology might circumvent or reduce the need for tritium in 
efficient modern warheads 
coauthoring the mark article were paul l leventhal president 
of the nuclear control institute milton m hoenig the institutes 
scientific director and retired rear adm thomas d davies former 
assistant director of the us arms control and disarmament agency 
</TEXT>
