<TEXT>
new york doctors soon will be able to tell 
needlesharing or sexual partners of aidsinfected people that 
theyre in danger of contracting the fatal disease under a bill 
signed thursday by gov mario cuomo 
the measure gives doctors legal immunity if they act in good 
faith when informing people they are at risk of getting the hiv 
virus which causes acquired immune deficiency syndrome the law 
stipulates that doctors cant tell people the name of the 
aidsinfected person only that someone close to them has 
contracted the disease 
the law gives doctors or the public health officials they wish 
to designate the option of informing people of the aids danger it 
doesnt require them to do so 
current state law offers legal immunity to doctors who inform 
people when they are at risk of getting certain other sexually 
transmitted diseases 
the new law requires written consent before testing for the hiv 
virus is done counseling must also be given before and after the 
test 
the law which goes into effect feb 1 1989 restricts the 
disclosure of aids test results including by court order or when 
the test subject authorizes release of the information 
cuomo said the law would increase the number of aids tests in 
new york 
were trying to get people to come forward willingly and allow 
themselves to be tested submit themselves to counseling and to the 
help that we have to offer them cuomo said 
new york with more than 16000 confirmed cases has the 
nations highest incidence of aids the state health department 
estimates that about 46000 new yorkers will have contracted aids 
by 1991 
aids is transmitted through sexual contact needles shared by 
drug abusers infected blood or blood products and from pregnant 
women to their offspring there is no cure for the disease which 
damages the bodys immune system 
david hansel legal services director of the new york citybased 
gay mens health crisis said the billrecognizes that the key to 
stemming the spread of the hiv virus is to encourage individuals 
at risk to be counseled and tested 
the maximum penalty for improperly disclosing test information 
is a year in jail and a 5000 fine 
</TEXT>
