<TEXT>
the fifth and final test of seals and 
joints on the redesigned space shuttle booster rocket went smoothly 
thursday according to engineers at the marshall space flight 
center 
based on all appearances the test was a complete success 
said jim thomas technical assistant to the manager of the solid 
rocket motor project 
the twominute static test firing with the booster segment 
anchored in a 25 million test stand put launchstyle pressure on 
joints redesigned after the challenger disaster 
this fifth test increases our confidence level and improves 
our engineering understanding of the redesigned joints thomas 
said i believe the test data will show that we have a 
reproducible and reliable design 
the seals are designed to keep internal hot gases inside the 
twin rockets that help kick shuttles into orbit 
the failure of a joint in one of challengers two boosters was 
blamed for the jan 28 1986 explosion that killed all seven crew 
members 
the national aeronautics and space administration hopes to 
launch the space shuttle discovery from the kennedy space center in 
florida by the last week of september marshall is responsible for 
shuttle propulsion systems including the booster rockets 
thursdays test was the fifth time marshall engineers have 
pressurized and then examined the new joints the four previous 
tests all have shown the new designs properly seal joints even when 
damaged 
weve done four other tests and thats all that was in the 
program said marshall spokesman jim solley but we had time to 
do one more and wanted to get all the additional data we could 
the 548000pound booster segment was fired for sixtenths of a 
second and then pressurized for 120 seconds 
booster maker morton thiokol inc testfires fullscale boosters 
in the utah desert at its wasatch proving grounds 
