<TEXT>
the writer traveled frequently to burma in the 
past decade as the associated press bureau chief in neighboring 
thailand burma now is closed to outsiders because of the upheavals 
there but in this dispatch he looks back at what led burmas 
summer of turmoil and what might be in store when it is over 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
before he toppled burmas civilian 
democracy gen ne win decried military interference in politics 
after taking power he promised a burmese way brand of 
socialism that would bring prosperity 
each man he said would be able to buy at least four 
saronglike longyis a year 
a quarter century later ne wins burmese way has turned out 
to be the wrong way for burmese 
his nation potentially one of asias most prosperous is 
formally classified as among the worlds neediest 
the country now is in upheaval with soldiers gunning down 
demonstrators daring to go into the streets to demand a democratic 
system now that ne win has announced his retirement the very 
defiance of the crowds in itself presents a serious challenge to a 
military seeking to maintain an authoritarian grip on the country 
but the embers setting off the explosions in the streets today 
apparently have been smouldering for years 
like many necessities in burma after 26 years of the burmese 
way the simple longyis worn by most men have become luxury items 
their price has risen 1500 percent since ne wins promise in 
1962 while wages have gone up a mere 35 percent 
with the price of a longyi now equivalent to a months wages for 
the average burmese ne wins promise has been relegated to a host 
of other blasted expectations about the man and his system 
some analysts maintain the 77yearold ne win who retired july 
23 is still pulling the political strings in burma where mass 
demonstrations have been directed at tearing down his political and 
economic structure 
others believe that ne win ailing and perhaps shaken by the 
course of events has truly stepped aside 
in either case the legacies of ne win oneparty rule 
isolationism ethnic insurgencies and his burmese way have 
sunk tenacious roots and could prove difficult to remove 
since his retirement ne win has been succeeded by widely 
disliked former general sein lwin and then by a civilian lawyer 
maung maung the current leader both are ne win loyalists sein 
lwin resorted to shooting hundreds of demonstrators and jailing 
vocal opponents to stay in power the short time he did 
ne win has created an apparatus with a vested interest in 
being perpetuated said one senior us government official at 
least two generations of military officers have a stake in keeping 
the system intact 
josef silverstein a leading american scholar on burma says 
effecting miracle solutions to burmas myriad problems would 
require the men in power to abandon the system and sack 
themselves then a good deal of ne wins work could be undone he 
believes if enough capable people came forward to take over 
beset by as many as a million demonstrators after he took over 
maung maung has promised to pave the way to democracy and usher in 
wideranging economic reforms but some skepticism exists because 
the governments word so far has been unreliable past promises of 
reforms including some made to major foreign aid donors either 
have not been kept or proved cosmetic 
a poster recently on a wall in rangoon the capital read 26 
years in vain 26 years of pain 
in the political field dismantling ne wins legacy would mean 
dissolving the 11 millionmember burma socialist program party and 
an array of institutions from the village level up created to 
support the sole power center 
it would also mean clipping the wings of an entrenched military 
bestriding the apex of the system was ne win charming 
ruthless and cunning maintaining what many analysts say was a 
greater hold on power than virtually any of the worlds dictatorial 
figures 
outright opponents were jailed or fled the country a half dozen 
rising stars within ne wins own ranks from vice chief of staff 
kyaw zaw in 1957 to brig tin oo in 1983 were dismissed or 
imprisoned 
thus ne win has seemingly left burma without any viable 
leaders within or outside the system antigovernment forces 
having nobody to turn to invoke heroic figures from the past 
diplomats describe the top government and party ranks as generally 
unimpressive 
theyre from the back row of the chorus line said max 
mcgrath a former journalist in rangoon and spokesman for burmese 
emigres in london 
robert h taylor a burma scholar at the university of london 
believes some of burmas current turmoil can be attributed to a 
struggle for leadership succession 
ne win pulls out his thumb and the dam collapses taylor 
said in an interview 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880901-0251 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
in the economic field ne wins centralized socialism has long 
tottered on the edge of total collapse and western experts say only 
a major policy reorientation largescale foreign investment and 
new welltrained economic managers can reverse the downward spiral 
the burmese way forced the expulsion of some 200000 indians 
and chinese who formed much of the entrepreneurial class and 
impelled thousands of burmans including members of one of the best 
civil services the british colonials left behind to seek new lives 
abroad 
closing its doors to private investment the government set up 
23 state corporations staffed largely by officials fearful of 
making even trivial decisions and by the governments own 
admission susceptible to corruption 
privately burmese say the only successful entity has been 
corporation 24 the vast black market fed by border smugglers 
on which citizens must rely for everything from matches to 
medicines by contrast the shelves of government stores are barely 
stocked factories operate far below capacity and a 4 billion 
foreign debt makes even essential imports problematic 
another vast drain on the economy has been the war rangoon wages 
against rebels from a dozen ethnic minorities who demand the 
greater autonomy once promised them 
although ethnic dissent flared before 1962 the insurgencies 
have intensified greatly under ne win who refused reconciliation 
except under his own terms instead the armed forces were built up 
to the current 185000 level and more than 30 percent of the annual 
budget is being spent on what has proved an unwinnable war 
silverstein regards the civil war as perhaps ne wins most 
odious legacy one that has exacerbated previously existing 
tensions between the burman majority and minority groups 
it prevents the emergence of a genuine national feeling 
amongst the peoples of burma silverstein said in an interview 
in its relations to the outside world ne win laid down strict 
neutralism and isolationism as cornerstones of policy 
haunted by the british colonial yoke and exploitation by 
outsiders beset by fears of being drawn into conflicts such as 
were then engulfing vietnam laos and cambodia burma retreated 
into a hermit existence it kept all superpowers at arms length 
and ousted foreigners and their decadent alien culture 
little touched by western influences spared the ills of rapid 
development picturesque burma captivates many outsiders crime 
pollution heart attacks are rare closely knitfamily life and 
traditions vanishing in other parts of asia remain strong 
the reassertion of burmeseness rightly or wrongly is going 
to be regarded in the minds of future burmese as a positive 
legacy silverstein said they will say we are still our own 
people doing things in our own way finding solutions within our 
own capabilities 
although the government claims to have preserved burmese 
culture there has been no evidence of fresh meaningful artistic 
or intellectual activity since 1962 
those who have money talk about burmese cultural purity 
said a senior us diplomat in 1977 those who dont will gladly 
trade their purity for rice 
during the ne win years annual per capita income stagnated at 
below 200 and the country was officially designated by the united 
nations last year as one of the worlds 41 least developed nations 
many burmese privately express shame at this turn of fortune 
seeing themselves far oustripped by neighbors with far fewer 
resources than this fabulously endowed country 
although burmas chaotic experiment with democracy was used by 
